The statement was released via his attorney, Eugene Fidell, after the charges were announced.

Last year, the Obama administration released five Taliban leaders in exchange for Bergdahl's return - but the celebration of his release was shortlived after his former comrades came forward and said he had deserted his post and forced them to carry out dangerous mission to try to find him.

Bergdahl faces a maximum sentence of life in prison if
convicted of the misbehavior charge.
He could also be reduced in rank to private, forfeit all salary
and be given a dishonorable discharge.

